"Kug J.-S., Choi D.-H., Jin F.-F., Kwon W.-T., Ren H.-L.","Role of synoptic eddy feedback on polar climate responses to the anthropogenic forcing",2010,"Geophysical Research Letters","37","14", L14704,"","",,,10.1029/2010GL043673,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-77955285212&partnerID=40&md5=eb1a0d53cd64cca92c9221ee0bcf6b99","Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sangrok gu, Ansan 426-744, South Korea; National Institute of Meteorological Research, KMA, 45 Gisangcheong-gil, Dongjak-gu, Seoul 156-720, South Korea; Department of Meteorology, SOEST, University of Hawaii at Manoa, 2525 Correa Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822, United States","Kug, J.-S., Korea Ocean Research and Development Institute, 1270 Sangrok gu, Ansan 426-744, South Korea; Choi, D.-H., National Institute of Meteorological Research, KMA, 45 Gisangcheong-gil, Dongjak-gu, Seoul 156-720, South Korea; Jin, F.-F., Department of Meteorology, SOEST, University of Hawaii at Manoa, 2525 Correa Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822, United States; Kwon, W.-T., National Institute of Meteorological Research, KMA, 45 Gisangcheong-gil, Dongjak-gu, Seoul 156-720, South Korea; Ren, H.-L., Department of Meteorology, SOEST, University of Hawaii at Manoa, 2525 Correa Rd., Honolulu, HI 96822, United States","Amplified polar warming and moistening under global warming are critical issues for the climate changes. The authors find that a poleward shift of the westerly jet stream and associated synoptic eddy feedback play a critical role in enhancing polar warming and moistening. Namely, the mean circulation changes due to anthropogenic forcing lead to the changes in storm feedbacks, which reinforce again climate responses, particularly the polar responses such as the enhanced polar warming and moistening. It is demonstrated here that the storm feedback can be explained by a simple rule based on the mean circulation change. This rule can be used for understanding other regional climate responses to the anthropogenic forcing. © 2010 by the American Geophysical Union.",,"Global warming; Storms; Anthropogenic forcing; Circulation changes; Critical issues; Jet streams; Poleward shift; Regional climate; Simple rules; Feedback; climate effect; climate feedback; eddy; global warming; human activity; jet stream; nature-society relations; polar meteorology; storm; synoptic meteorology; westerly",,,,,,"Alexeev, V.A., Langen, P.L., Bates, J.R., Polar amplification of surface warming on an aquaplanet in ""ghost forcing"" experiments without sea ice feedbacks (2005) Climate Dynamics, 24 (7-8), pp. 655-666. , DOI 10.1007/s00382-005-0018-3; Cai, M., Dynamical greenhouse-plus feedback and polar warming amplification. Part I: A dry radiative-transportive climate model (2006) Clim. Dyn., 26, pp. 661-675. , doi:10.1007/s00382-005-0104-6; Cai, M., Lu, J., Dynamical greenhouse-plus feedback and polar warming amplification. Part II: Meridional and vertical asymmetries of the global warming (2007) Climate Dynamics, 29 (4), pp. 375-391. , DOI 10.1007/s00382-007-0238-9; Cubasch, U., Projections of future climate change, in Climate Change 2001: The Scientific Basis (2001) Contribution of Working Group i to the Third Assessment Report of the Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change, pp. 525-582. , edited by J. T. Houghton et al Cambridge Univ. Press, Cambridge, U. K; Graversen, R.G., Vertical structure of recent Arctic warming (2008) Nature, 451, pp. 53-56. , doi:10.1038/nature06502; Holland, M.M., Bitz, C.M., Polar amplification of climate change in coupled models (2003) Climate Dynamics, 21 (3-4), pp. 221-232. , DOI 10.1007/s00382-003-0332-6; Jin, F.-F., Pan, L.-L., Watanabe, M., Dynamics of synoptic eddy and low-frequency flow interaction. Part I: A linear closure (2006) Journal of the Atmospheric Sciences, 63 (7), pp. 1677-1694. , DOI 10.1175/JAS3715.1; Jin, F.-F., Pan, L.-L., Watanabe, M., Dynamics of synoptic eddy and low-frequency flow interaction. Part II: A theory for low-frequency modes (2